    {
        "content": "<p>In the \"In concrete terms\" section, you don't mean that the \"universal\" morphism is the (essentially) unique morphism together with 2-cells as indicated, but only the initial such morphism, right?</p>",
        "id": 276477972,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1648129880
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, for example, the \"laxer limit\" of the empty diagram in Cat could be any category with an initial object.</p>",
        "id": 276478614,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1648130207
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That seems kind of cool -- shades of Hilbert's <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\epsilon</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϵ</span></span></span></span> operator, no? A neat way to pick out the categories with initial objects.</p>",
